&lt;p&gt;The set of &lt;code&gt;possibles&lt;/code&gt; expands very rapidly, and kills my little
Chromebook with n &amp;gt;= 5.  So, the first optimization will be to cut
down on the number of possibles&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;some words will never contain certain elements.  I'm looking at
   you, Unununium (Uuu) and friends.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;English words never contain more than N (to be determined)
   consonants in a row.  So, eliminate them too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</summary></entry><entry><title>Sphinx autodoc-skip-member being ignored</title><link href="/sphinx-autodoc-skip-member-being-ignored.html" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2015-07-20T00:00:00+01:00</updated><author><name>gravenimage</name></author><id>tag:,2015-07-20:sphinx-autodoc-skip-member-being-ignored.html</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Argh, I've just struggled for an hour to figure out why the results of
my &lt;code&gt;autodoc-skip-member&lt;/code&gt; handler in Sphinx are consistently being ignored....&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It's because&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a) you can only have &lt;em&gt;one&lt;/em&gt; handler (app.connect does not chain handlers), and&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b) I am using the &lt;code&gt;napoleon&lt;/code&gt; extension, which installs its own
autodoc-skip-member handler.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my particular case, I needed to skip all special members
(e.g. &lt;code&gt;__dict__&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;__str__&lt;/code&gt; etc).  Luckily, napoleon allows you to add
this to your conf.py:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;napoleon_include_special_with_doc = False
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</summary></entry><entry><title>Acer C720 Chromebook AwesomeWM keyboard setup</title><link href="/acer-c720-chromebook-awesomewm-keyboard-setup.html" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2014-12-21T00:00:00+00:00</updated><author><name>gravenimage</name></author><id>tag:,2014-12-21:acer-c720-chromebook-awesomewm-keyboard-setup.html</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;The Acer C720 is a lovely little web-browsing machine, and with
&lt;a href="https://github.com/dnschneid/crouton"&gt;Crouton&lt;/a&gt; can potentially be
useful to a geekier audience.  But with a limited screensize and a
poor trackpad, it's sensible to go down the tiling WM route.  Crouton
details instructions for using AwesomeWM which worked out of the box.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Almost.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I've used emacs for years and have the muscle-memory to prove it.
Specifically, I have the memory linked to a swapped control and capslock key.
The capslock key which is now &lt;code&gt;mod4&lt;/code&gt; and controls AwesomeWM shortcuts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Because this specific Chromebook (or is it all of them?) doesn't have
the Windows key, the only available key to use for WM-commands is the
&lt;code&gt;alt gr&lt;/code&gt; key.  It's a bit un-ergonomic, but a lot less than resetting
years of experience.  Here's the &lt;code&gt;.Xmodmap&lt;/code&gt; file to do both the
remapping of the search key to ctrl, and &lt;code&gt;alt gr&lt;/code&gt; to &lt;code&gt;mod4&lt;/code&gt;.  Set this
from your &lt;code&gt;.xinitrc&lt;/code&gt; or just run it in the first console you create.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre&gt;clear control
clear mod4
clear mod1
keycode 133 = Super_L
keycode 108 = Super_R
keycode 64 = Alt_L
add control  = Control_L Control_R Super_L
add mod4 = Hyper_L Super_R
add mod1 = Alt_L
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</summary></entry></feed>